Participants agreed that the medical compatibility between donor and recipient characteristics is a nonnegotiable prerequisite for donor organ allocation. When talking about comorbidities, they agreed that these have an influence on the effectiveness of a transplantation.
You have to draw a line somewhere. We have too few organs and therefore I would select by chance of success. In addition, if somebody has possibly soon-to-be lethal co-morbidities, then I am sorry, but they should not receive an organ. That’s throwing pearls before swine. […] And if it was me, I honestly have to say that I would understand that. Bad luck. But life has to end at some point. That’s how I would explain it to myself. And maybe then it is salvation. Especially with such comorbidities. – Interview 01
